	5. @PostContruct - By putting @PostConstruct on a method, you tell Spring: 
					  "Wait until the object is completely built AND all its dependencies are 
					   plugged in. The very second that setup is done, run this method automatically."
					   
					   
					   @Component
					   public class CacheManager {

							@Autowired
							private ProductRepository productRepository; // Spring injects this in Step 2

							private List<String> productCache;

							// 1. Constructor runs first (productRepository is still null here!)
							public CacheManager() { } 

							// 2. Spring injects the productRepository...

							// 3. NOW this runs automatically!
							@PostConstruct
							public void init() {
								// Safe to use productRepository now! It is not null.
								this.productCache = productRepository.findAllNames();
								System.out.println("Cache successfully loaded after dependency injection!");
							}
					  }
					   
	6. @Predestroy   If @PostConstruct is the "Welcome to life" alarm, @PreDestroy is the "Graceful Death" warning.
					 When your application shuts down (for example, you stop your Tomcat server or restart your Spring Boot app),
					 Spring destroys all your objects to free up the computer's RAM.
					 Why do we need it?
					 Imagine your Java object opened a heavy connection to a remote file server or 
  					 a cloud bucket. If Spring just kills your object instantly, that network connection
   	 				 might stay hanging open on the server, wasting resources and bandwidth.
   	 				 
   	 				 "Clean Up Before You Leave"

					 By putting @PreDestroy on a method, you tell Spring: "Hey, right before you 
	  				physically delete this object from memory, let me clean up my mess first."
	  				
	  				
	  				
	  				By putting @PreDestroy on a method, you are telling Spring: 
	  				"Hey, the cleaning crew is about to delete me. Before they wipe 
	  				me out, give me 1 second to run this specific method so I can turn 
	  				off the lights and close my files safely."
	  				
					@Component
					public class DatabaseBackupService {

						private FileWriter backupFile;

						// ... your application runs and writes data to the file ...

						@PreDestroy
						public void closeEverything() {
							// Spring calls this AUTOMATICALLY right before deleting this object
							try {
								if (backupFile != null) {
									backupFile.flush(); // Make sure the last piece of data is saved
									backupFile.close(); // Safely unlock the file
									System.out.println("File saved and closed safely. Goodbye!");
								}
							} catch (IOException e) {
								e.printStackTrace();
							}
						}
					}
					
					The moment the application shuts down or decides it doesn't 
					need that Bean anymore, Spring steps in just before the 
					Garbage Collector wipes it out and says: "Hold on, let 
					me check this object for any @PreDestroy notes." Spring 
					then runs that method completely, and only after it finishes 
					does the Garbage Collector delete the object from memory.

					There is just one very important rule you need to know about 
					how this works under the hood.

					The Crucial Rule: Only ONE Method
					You can have multiple methods in your class, but Spring will 
					only look for the specific one marked with the @PreDestroy badge.

			 		If your object is dying, only the method with the @PreDestroy
			 		annotation gets called. The other regular methods are 
			 		completely ignored.
			 		
			 		@Component
					public class MyService {

						// ❌ This does NOT get called when the object dies
						public void printHello() {
							System.out.println("Hello");
						}

						// ❌ This does NOT get called when the object dies
						public void doSomething() {
							System.out.println("Working...");
						}

						//  THIS IS THE ONLY ONE THAT RUNS!
						@PreDestroy
						public void cleanUpBeforeDeath() {
							System.out.println("Closing database lines now!");
						}
					}
	  				
